"title": "7335: circumcision, physical",
"media_type": "Text",
"index_reference": "7335",
"language": "eng",
"review_level": "None",
"content": "<p>In the OT, circumcision is seen as an outward sign of membership of Israel, the people of God.</p>\n<h2>The significance of circumcision in God's covenant with Abraham</h2>\n<p><strong><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Gen17:10-Gen17:14\">GEN 17:10–17:14</a></strong> <em>See also</em> <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Acts7:8\">ACT 7:8</a></p>\n<h3>Circumcision is also for Abraham's descendants</h3>\n<p><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Gen17:7\">GEN 17:7</a></p>\n<h2>Circumcision as a sign of national identity</h2>\n<p>Dinah's brothers and the Shechemites:\n <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Gen34:8-Gen34:9\">GEN 34:8–34:9</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Gen34:14-Gen34:17\">GEN 34:14–34:17</a>; \n<a href=\"https://ref.ly/Exod4:24-Exod4:26\">EXO 4:24–4:26</a>; ; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Josh5:4-Josh5:8\">JOS 5:4–5:8</a></p>\n<h2>Circumcision is integrated into the Mosaic law</h2>\n<p><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Lev12:3\">LEV 12:3</a>; ; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/John7:22\">JHN 7:22</a> <em>It was later sometimes forgotten that circumcision predated the Mosaic law.</em></p>\n<h2>Circumcision as an important Passover restriction</h2>\n<p><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Exod12:44\">EXO 12:44</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Exod12:48-Exod12:49\">EXO 12:48–12:49</a>; ; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Judg14:3\">JDG 14:3</a> <em>Some of Israel's neighbours practised circumcision, but not the Philistines.</em></p>\n<h2>Circumcision was not necessarily a sign of consecration to God</h2>\n<p><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Jer9:25-Jer9:26\">JER 9:25–9:26</a></p>\n<h2>NT accounts of circumcision practised in obedience to the law</h2>\n<p><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Luke1:59\">LUK 1:59</a> <em>John</em>; ; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Luke2:21\">LUK 2:21</a> <em>Jesus Christ</em>; ; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/John7:23\">JHN 7:23</a> <em>Circumcision was permitted on the Sabbath</em>; ; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Phil3:5\">PHP 3:5</a> <em>Paul refers to his own circumcision</em>; ; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Acts16:3\">ACT 16:3</a> <em>Timothy</em></p>\n<h2>The subject of circumcision debated by the first Christians</h2>\n<p><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Acts10:45\">ACT 10:45</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Acts11:2\">ACT 11:2</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Acts15:5\">ACT 15:5</a>; ; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Gal2:3\">GAL 2:3</a> <em>That Titus, a Greek, was not required to be circumcised illustrates the change in the attitude of the church concerning the relevance of the law to Gentile believers</em>; ; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Eph2:11\">EPH 2:11</a>; ; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Col3:11\">COL 3:11</a>; ; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Titus1:10\">TIT 1:10</a></p>",
